<DOC><DOCNO> AP881111-0286 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1817EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Southland     11-11 0277</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Earns-Southland,0286</SECOND><HEAD>Southland Posts $46.8 Million Loss in Third Quarter</HEAD><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Southland Corp. reported Friday that it lost $46.8million in the third quarter ended Sept. 30 because of interest andother expenses related to the leveraged buyout of the company lastDecember.   Southland, the nation's largest convenience store chain, had anet loss of $3.7 million in the same period in 1987.   But the company stressed that different accounting systems wereused during the two periods and the figures are not directlycomparable. Southland said it earned $17.5 million in July 1987,then lost $21.2 million in the following two months.   Revenue in the third quarter was $2.18 billion. In the same threemonths of last year, Southland's revenue was $2.14 billion.   The company has completed a divestiture program designed to raisecapital to repay money borrowed for the buyout by its foundingfamily and management. Southland has sold 910 convenience stores andhas signed agreements to sell 168 more.   ``Through early November, we have already repaid approximately$880 million of our leveraged buyout bank debt, meeting ourprincipal repayment obligations on that debt up to December 1989,''said Southland President Jere Thompson.   In the first nine months of the year, Southland had a net loss of$179.2 million. In 1987, the company earned $90.1 million in theseven months before the buyout, then lost $21.2 million in the twomonths afterward.   Southland still has 7,000 7-Eleven and other convenience storeunits in the United States and Canada that are supported by fivedistribution centers and six food division plants. There also aremore than 5,000 7-Eleven stores operated by licensees and affiliates.</TEXT></DOC>